---
import { AUTHOR, SOCIAL_LINKS, TAGLINE } from '../consts';
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
	title="About / komo.sh"
	description="komo - a technologist working in automation. Small sharp tools, AI agents, and the boring plumbing that makes them work."
>
	<div class="wrap">
		<section class="hero">
			<div class="hero-grid">
				<div>
					<div class="prompt"><span class="g">$</span> cat about.md</div>
					<h1 class="page-title">whoami</h1>
					<p class="page-sub">{TAGLINE}</p>
				</div>
				<div class="about-card">
					<dl>
						<dt>name</dt>
						<dd>{AUTHOR.name}</dd>
						<dt>born</dt>
						<dd>{AUTHOR.born}</dd>
						<dt>edu</dt>
						<dd>{AUTHOR.edu}</dd>
						<dt>pronouns</dt>
						<dd>{AUTHOR.pronouns}</dd>
					</dl>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>

		<article class="prose" style="padding:34px 0 8px;">
			<p>{AUTHOR.bio}</p>
			<p>
				Most of what I do lives at the unglamorous layer: parsing messy inputs, wiring
				retries, and trusting an agent&apos;s output enough to stop babysitting it. The loop was
				never the hard part. I write here about the things that actually shipped, the ones
				that quietly died, and the habits that survived contact with production.
			</p>

			<h2>What you&apos;ll find here</h2>
			<ul>
				<li><b>Build logs</b> - small command-line tools and the decisions behind them.</li>
				<li><b>Agents, honestly</b> - what works and what is only a for-loop with polish.</li>
				<li><b>Plumbing</b> - parsing, retries, queues, cron, and the boring 80% nobody demos.</li>
			</ul>
		</article>

		<section class="blk about" style="border-bottom:none;padding-top:10px;">
			<div class="sec-head"><h2>Elsewhere</h2></div>
			<div class="topics" aria-label="Social links">
				{
					SOCIAL_LINKS.map((s) => (
						<a class="topic" href={s.href} target="_blank" rel="me noopener">
							<h3>{s.label}</h3>
							<p>Open profile</p>
						</a>
					))
				}
			</div>
		</section>
	</div>
</BaseLayout>
